Some background information on the behavior: By default and by design Word will use the same ***style*** definitions as defined in the *target* document so that content coming in is merged &quot;seemlessly&quot; (from a formatting perspective). If the in-coming content has the same style name(s) applied as already present in the target document, the formatting of in-coming content will change.

As shown in an answer, the `PasteAndFormat` with the parameter `Word.WdRecoveryType.wdFormatOriginalFormatting` method when using the Windows Clipboard will override the default behavior and maintain the original formatting.

Working via the Clipboard is not always desired or ideal, however. There is another way, which is to change the style name(s) in the source document so that they&#39;re different than in the target document. This approach will work if styles have been used *consistently* in the source document. (Formatting applied manually may still be lost, however.) 

The following code snippet illustrates the approach for paragraph styles. It creates a new style based on the styles used in the document - the new style is an exact duplicate except for the name. A Find/Replace is then performed to replace all instances of the style with the new style. Now the content can be inserted into another document and the formatting is maintained. 

        Word.Document doc = wdApp.ActiveDocument;
        Word.Style sOld = null;
        Word.Style sCopy = null;
        Word.Find f = doc.Content.Find;

        //Select Normal text, otherwise Normal will take on character formatting of current selected text
        Word.Selection sel = wdApp.Selection;
        sel.Find.set_Style(Word.WdBuiltinStyle.wdStyleNormal);
        sel.Find.Execute(&quot;&quot;, Type.Missing,
          Type.Missing, Type.Missing, Type.Missing, Type.Missing, true, Word.WdFindWrap.wdFindStop,
          true, Type.Missing, Type.Missing, Type.Missing, Type.Missing, Type.Missing, Type.Missing);

        foreach (Word.Style s in doc.Styles)
        {
            if ((s.InUse) &amp;&amp; (s.Type == Word.WdStyleType.wdStyleTypeParagraph) &amp;&amp; 
                (!s.NameLocal.Contains(&quot; Copy&quot;)))
            {
                sOld = s;
                sCopy = doc.Styles.Add(sOld.NameLocal + &quot; Copy&quot;, sOld.Type);
                sCopy.set_BaseStyle(sOld);
                f.set_Style(sOld);
                f.Replacement.set_Style(sCopy);
                f.Execute(&quot;&quot;, Type.Missing, 
                Type.Missing, Type.Missing, Type.Missing, Type.Missing, true, Word.WdFindWrap.wdFindStop, 
                true, &quot;&quot;, Word.WdReplace.wdReplaceAll, Type.Missing, Type.Missing, Type.Missing, Type.Missing);
            }
        }

